[36;1mNAME[0m
       pthread_create - create a new thread

[36;1mLIBRARY[0m
       POSIX threads library ([31;3;1mlibpthread[24;0m, [31;3;1m-lpthread[24;0m)

[36;1mSYNOPSIS[0m
       [36;1m#include <pthread.h>[0m

       [36;1mint pthread_create(pthread_t *restrict [31;3;1m[22;0mthread[24;0m[36;1m,[0m
                          [36;1mconst pthread_attr_t *_Nullable restrict [31;3;1m[22;0mattr[24;0m[36;1m,[0m
                          [36;1mtypeof(void *(void *_Nullable)) *[31;3;1m[22;0mstart_routine[24;0m[36;1m,[0m
                          [36;1mvoid *_Nullable restrict [31;3;1m[22;0marg[24;0m[36;1m);[0m

[36;1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       The  [36;1mpthread_create[22;0m()  function  starts  a  new  thread  in the calling
       process.  The new thread starts execution by invoking  [31;3;1mstart_routine[24;0m();
       [31;3;1marg[24;0m is passed as the sole argument of [31;3;1mstart_routine[24;0m().

       The new thread terminates in one of the following ways:

       •  It  calls  [36;1mpthread_exit[22;0m(3),  specifying an exit status value that is
          available  to  another  thread  in  the  same  process  that   calls
          [36;1mpthread_join[22;0m(3).

       •  It  returns  from  [31;3;1mstart_routine[24;0m().   This  is equivalent to calling
          [36;1mpthread_exit[22;0m(3) with the value supplied in the [31;3;1mreturn[24;0m statement.

       •  It is canceled (see [36;1mpthread_cancel[22;0m(3)).

       •  Any of the threads in the process calls [36;1mexit[22;0m(3), or the main  thread
          performs  a  return from [31;3;1mmain[24;0m().  This causes the termination of all
          threads in the process.

       The [31;3;1mattr[24;0m argument points to a [31;3;1mpthread_attr_t[24;0m structure  whose  contents
       are  used  at  thread creation time to determine attributes for the new
       thread; this structure is initialized  using  [36;1mpthread_attr_init[22;0m(3)  and
       related  functions.   If  [31;3;1mattr[24;0m is NULL, then the thread is created with
       default attributes.

       Before returning, a successful call to [36;1mpthread_create[22;0m() stores  the  ID
       of  the  new thread in the buffer pointed to by [31;3;1mthread[24;0m; this identifier
       is used to refer to the thread in subsequent calls  to  other  pthreads
       functions.

       The  new  thread  inherits  a copy of the creating thread’s signal mask
       ([36;1mpthread_sigmask[22;0m(3)).  The set of pending signals for the new thread is
       empty ([36;1msigpending[22;0m(2)).  The new thread does not  inherit  the  creating
       thread’s alternate signal stack ([36;1msigaltstack[22;0m(2)).

       The new thread inherits the calling thread’s floating‐point environment
       ([36;1mfenv[22;0m(3)).

       The  initial  value  of  the  new  thread’s  CPU‐time  clock  is 0 (see
       [36;1mpthread_getcpuclockid[22;0m(3)).

   [36;1mLinux‐specific details[0m
       The new thread inherits copies of the calling thread’s capability  sets
       (see [36;1mcapabilities[22;0m(7)) and CPU affinity mask (see [36;1msched_setaffinity[22;0m(2)).

[36;1mRETURN VALUE[0m
       On  success,  [36;1mpthread_create[22;0m() returns 0; on error, it returns an error
       number, and the contents of [31;3;1m*thread[24;0m are undefined.

